Parliament did not support an amendment to liberate Tymoshenko
The Ukraine Parliament has today rejected the proposal of repealing the amendment of the section of the Criminal Code which condemns opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko.
The amendment would open the way to the release of the former Minister, but members of Parliament rejected the proposal to reduce sentences for economic crimes in the second reading.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for the alleged signing of an agreement with Russia disadvantageous for Ukraine on purchase of natural gas.
The judgment is not yet firm, the Court of appeal is obliged to review in December.
Tymoshenko was convinced that it was a political revenge of the regime, and even in the West raised doubts about the impartiality of the tribunal.
The proposal to withdraw paragraph 365 of the Criminal Code which were sentenced the former first Minister was supported by 147 members in the vote.
226 Votes were needed for approval.
