How have travel prices evolved since 1989
Until 1989 in then Czechoslovakia had only five State travel agents authorised: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The time travel agencies sold travel only to the Socialist bloc, in the majority of cases because travel to the West were very restricted.
Czech tourists would, therefore, on vacation to the beaches of the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union, (Crimea on the Black Sea Sochi) Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when he could travel to Yugoslavia, however, after the Yugoslav regime moved westward and the Czech tourists trips were then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact to the citizens of the Socialist bloc (i.e. also to the Checoeslovacos) not be enabling them travel free and individually even in the socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or to the Soviet Union, needed a letter of invitation, if not, the individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies offered in those days also travel West, but one should be at the tail with a sack of sleep and thus spend all night, or have "good friends" in the Agency.
Yet all was not won.
The so-called "promise of change" that was the condition for travel to the West, was not granted to the "people politically unreliable", so could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a currency freely convertible and without guarantee of change, it was not possible to obtain (the Western currency) resources to travel to the West.
The vast majority of the Czechs spent your holidays in their own country, so it had a large number of cottages and summer homes, the Czechs were acquiring. This custom still persists.
How to travel from the Czech Republic has suffered since 1989 a revolution.
While until 1989 for us was not more will spend the holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs took 4.5 million holiday trips to countries around the world.
It is nna great paradox that today day are no longer aware, the fact that to the destination currently favorite, Croatia, until 1989 not you could travel freely, because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
Early 1990s won exemption from visa to travel to the neighbouring States of Western Europe, which caused a huge wave of visits of short duration, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The checoeslovacos, for a long time, were not had enough of the excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it at the least for a moment.
For example, in Paris sleeping groups of Czechs in the parks in tents, that our income then do not allow us to pay for a hotel or pension.
A typical feature of the Czechs at the time was the take with you the food (canned foods, sausages, etc.) to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech Crown, so our tourists could finally, after decades, buy freely Western currency.
Our standard of living increased and with it also the average wages, around 1997 causing an increase in demand for travel.
With the increase in demand for travel began agencies, from 1997 on a regular basis, prepare travel using Charter flights connections, what did incredibly lower travel prices compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts by the volume of passengers.
At the end of the 90s of the last century, already the Czechs traveled without a visa to almost all developed countries, except United States.UU., which further simplified our trips.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism already happened in 2000, when it was organized, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from Czech Republic to an exotic country, and went to Thailand.
Depart every year from that year, direct Charter flights with Czech tourists was hot and distant countries. This winter is already directly flies from Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
Exotic countries currently visiting about 100 thousand Czechs per year.
Another interesting moment of this era, that symbolizes our development post-revolution, arrived in 2008.
November 17, 2008, EE.UU. It eliminated visas for Czech visitors, with what our country came to be among the more developed countries of the world.
In 2008 the Czechs for the first time in its history, have spent more than half of their holiday abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in its history, have been spent in travel abroad more than 15 thousand Czech Crowns per head, including expenditure on the site of stay.
