The appointed Italian Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet Wednesday with President Italy to present the new Government that will face a crisis that has placed Italy on the brink of economic disaster and has endangered the eurozone.
A statement from the Presidential Palace announced that Monti, named on Sunday, will meet Wednesday with the President, Giorgio Napolitano, to confirm that it can form a Government.
He is expected to present a Cabinet composed mostly of technocrats, although it is not clear when the new Executive will assume the position.
Monti said that it would submit to the Chairman the outcome of his talks with political parties in his attempt to form a Government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in the ability of our country to overcome this difficult phase," the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not say explicitly that you can form a Government, but the tone of their comments indicated that the obstacles have been overcome.
The "framework is now well outlined," he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a Government in less than three days, much less than usual, while Italy fought a political and financial crisis that has driven the cost of its debt to unsustainable levels.
The new administration led by the former European Commissioner Monti must adopt a hard austerity package demanded by European leaders to restore battered confidence in Italy.
Underlining the pressure on Monti to give prisa, the volatility of the markets placed the BTP Italian bond yields, 10 years over 7 per cent, the level at which Greece and Ireland were forced to be rescued.
