"We believe that the efforts of Professor Monti are destined to have a good result," he told the press Angelino Alfano, Secretary of the centre-right party.
The support of the LDP, the biggest party in Italy, is significant because until now many of its members had opposed the Government of majority technocrat who is forming Monti.
Parliamentary support
Monti's new Government must have a strong parliamentary support to implement what are likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blocking or delay in their efforts could lead to a new and devastating attack of the financial markets.
The Italian Association of foreign banks joined the pressure by warning that a failure of Monti would be a disaster.
Monti began Monday his consultations with political parties, unions and business groups, as well as with youth organizations and women.
It put an end to his round of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was named Sunday by Napolitano, which has enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi he would resign, Italian debt costs have now turned to critical levels between the uncertainty about whether the new Prime Minister will be successful.
Rescue Italy, with a public debt of 1.8 billion euros, would be too much for the current financial defences of the eurozone.
