Nord Stream, new gateway of the Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, which connects directly Western Europe with Russia passing through the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has been in service.
You must supply gas to meet the needs of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, has wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
On Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four heads of State and Government, participated on the shores of the Baltic, between the music of the Orchestra and a delicate buffet, at the opening of Nord Stream, the new gas pipeline linking directly, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, Prime Minister François Fillon French and his counterpart of the Netherlands, Mark Rutte, the wheel of the valve that controls the entry of Russian gas in Western Europe network have revolved together.
With this new pipeline, each year reach 27.5 billion cubic metres of Russian gas additional Western Europe through a first had of 1,224 km that connect the region of St. Petersburg with the Land of Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania.
A second tube should be concluded by the end of 2012 which allow you to supply a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, i.e., sufficient to cover all French consumption.
In addition, talk is of the possibility of constructing a third tube by the same route.
For Gazprom, the completion time of this huge work presents victory aires.
Poland and the Baltic countries had been strongly opposed to the project.
In fact, Nord Stream will allow to supply gas directly to Germany, avoiding the Earth course by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries lost some of their power: for them, it will be more difficult to influence Russia threatening to close access to the markets of Western Europe.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had no hesitation in comparing Nord Stream as a "new compact German-Soviet", referring to the Alliance between Hitler and Stalin to deal with Poland in 1939.
That is, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project has obtained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of the energy Europe, given that the project has created a gap between the East and the West Europeans.
Russia has, in just five years, do succeed his vision of a direct partnership between Russia and Western countries rich, large consumers of gas and with more limited reserves.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that unites us organically," confirmed François Fillon during the inauguration of the pipeline, showing to what extent large contracts for the gas sector are as political as economic.
All of this explains the broad smiles on the faces of the directors of Gazprom, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The undersea tube is made of steel covered with cement to protect against the anchors of vessels.
It relies on the bottom of the sea, to an average of 200 m of depth.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating from World War II.
"It was necessary to remove or destroy a hundred of them, by precaution," said Jens Müller, spokesman of the company Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to intensify the measures for the protection of fauna and flora.
The tube is a long snake of metal which weighs as 242 Eiffel Towers and is not interrupted in its entire length: valves, nor maintenance stations.
A control in the waters of Sweden platform was planned, but those responsible for the project renounced it to see that the Swedes were not very willing to allow that a society State Russian be established permanently in the sea off its coast.
"In the event of breakdown, means the passage of gas in less than a minute", accurate Jens Müller.
In case of leakage, gas from the pipeline be released, therefore, into the atmosphere.
But builders consider it unlikely that produce an escape, because they have provided for joints which, according to forecasts, will have a flight every 100,000 years.
The State of the pipeline control is guaranteed through a submarine robot, dragged by a ship, which conducts field inspections, as well as a device that circulates through the interior of the pipeline.
Shaped like a cigar, it enters the interior of the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, provides accurate data on possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline has been designed to work for 50 years without any kind of repair.
The movement of the gas is guaranteed just by pressure.
At the beginning is of 200 bars and out of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the shares.
She joined the German E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It is headquartered in German, Switzerland, where enforcement is especially favourable.
Later, Gazprom leased to the society, for a renewable period of twenty-five years, all of the capabilities of gas transportation.
"Gazprom will pay by the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas that is actually transported", accurate Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline has been just 30% with the contribution of the shareholders and 70% through bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach 7.4 billion euros for two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that will not exceed your investment, because Gazprom assumes only the risk of costs alone.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted pines.
A few valves, with 4.5 meters high, form the gas exit door.
There are a few sensors that measure pressure, temperature and the specific characteristics of the gas on arrival, before that you transfer to German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
Total capacity, shall be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
