Is the unemployment rate of disabled workers why still so high?
About 19% of persons with disabilities, they are looking for a job.
15Th week for the employment of disabled persons begins today.
Despite a public policy resolved, applied since 2005, the unemployment rate among the disabled twice the average rate: 19%, compared with 9 per cent for the population as a whole.
Disappointing?
"No," says Eric Blanchet, director-general of Adapt, the Association which organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
"Progress for fifteen years are substantial."
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average."
"However, there is still a lot to do".
It is worth mentioning that the disabled unemployed still face numerous obstacles to access to employment.
They tend to have a more advanced age: 37% has more than 50 years (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% is not finished high school and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread among them: 53% for the disabled, compared with 38% on average.
I.e., there are numerous issues hindering the return to the world of work especially and which "constitute the crux of the problem", says Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies to hire disabled workers.
These are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those that are not mentioned; the mindset of the people is moving, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS – Entreprendre for la Cité Association indicated that surveyed managers have "a level of knowledge about disabilities low", with an "over-representation of persons" in wheelchair, poor physical or intellectuals.
The result: companies with more than 20 workers are a far cry from the objective of hiring a 6% of disabled workers, objective that was set in a law of... 1987.
According to the latest available figures, dating from 2008, reaching a ratio of 2.6%.
"Now reached about 3 %", says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the body responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not respect this law.
The proof: the number of "subject to this contribution" establishment, as well as the margin amounts have declined between 2007 and 2011, passing 59.000 to 46,000 structures (and 606 to 480 million euros).
"The Act of 2005, which increased contributions, has generated pressure for companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
But this improvement also reflects a real awareness, in particular among large groups.
According to the Ministry of labour, only 59% of companies possessing between 20 and 49 employees has disabled employees in its workforce, compared to 82% of companies between 100 and 199 employees.
